While Ri reiterated well-known North Korean complaints about Washington's opposition to a "phased" approach to nuclear disarmament, where North Korea would be rewarded if they took gradual steps, his speech seemed important, however, as it did not unequivocally reject unilateral disarmament, as has previously been the case from Pyongyang.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first ever summit between a incumbent US president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, where Kim promised to work "nuclear disarmament on the Korean peninsula" while Trump promised to guarantee North Korea's security.
North Korea has called for a formal end to the Korean War that took place in 1950-53, but the United States has said that Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also shown resistance to softening harsh international sanctions against North Korea.
“The United States insists on ‘nuclear disarmament first’ and expands the pressure with sanctions to achieve their purpose by coercion and even opposes the ‘declaration of the end of the war’,” Ri said.
