Harvard students take a course on getting enough sleep
A new course at Harvard University has given all undergraduate students more sleep. The aim of the course is to counteract the growing macho culture, where you study all night long supported by large amounts of caffeine.
A researcher has shown that students at the world’s best university often have no idea the first thing about taking care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at the Brigham and Women's Hospital, has created the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He got the idea for the course after giving a presentation about the effects of sleep deprivation on learning.
“When the presentation was finished, a girl came up to me and said, ‘Why do I only get to know this now that I’m on the candidate?’
“She said no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, which is offered for the first time this year, explains to students how good sleeping habits can improve one’s academic and sporting performance as well as one’s overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and CEO of the university’s health field, said the university has decided to offer the course after finding out that students were in severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The hour-long course consists of, among other things, various interactive exercises.
In one of the exercises, there is a picture of a dorm room where students have to click on coffee cups, curtains, running shoes and books to get knowledge about the effects of caffeine and light, and how one’s sporting performance is affected by sleep deprivation, and how important good sleeping habits are.
In another part of the course, participants hear about how long-term sleep deprivation increases the risk of heart attacks, blood clots, depression and cancer.
Participants are encouraged to think about their daily habits by clicking on various icons on an interactive map of the campus.
“We know that it won’t change the behavior of students immediately.
But we think they have a right to know - just as you have a right to know how cigarettes affect health," Professor Czeisler adds.
The pride in taking an “allnighter” still exists, he says, adding that modern technology and increased pressure on students have meant that sleep deprivation is a growing problem.
The “secret weapon” against stress, exhaustion and anxiety is good and sufficient sleep, he said – it even discourages weight gain because sleep deprivation makes the brain think you’re starving, which is why they’re constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies chemical and physical biology, last year helped Professor Czeisler organize the course when he took one of his courses in his first year at Harvard.
He said the course had opened his eyes and had him work on making it a general course throughout the university.
He hopes that next, all graduates will be offered a similar course before continuing their education.
Professor Czeisler advises students to set an alarm so that they know when to go to bed and when to get up. This can create awareness of the harmful effects of light from electronic screens, which can shift the circadian rhythm and make it harder to fall asleep.
